California has taken on the Trump Administration on many fronts, but now it's challenging the president on his home turf: Twitter.

Today Gov. Brown's top aide warned that if the Department of Interior recommends allowing oil or gas drilling, timber harvesting or mining in national monuments in the state, California will take "swift legal action."

&nbsp;

https://twitter.com/NancyEMcFadden/status/900122733509464065

The threat came ahead of recommendations from Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke, whose review of recently-designated national monuments is expected to be made public today. Zinke ordered staff to review nearly two dozen  monuments, to determine if federal prohibitions against energy extraction and other industrial activities should be removed. Zinke could also advise President Trump to shrink the size of some areas.

The monuments in Californa stretch across the state and include Berryessa Snow Mountains, Carrizo Plain, Giant Sequoia, Mojave Trails and the San Gabriel Mountains.

